/* RAIL.CPP - Handling the setting up and detecting of rails
 
A Rail is a grindable line in the game.  This is set up as a series of linked nodes.
(See trig.cpp for more on nodes).  Each rail node is linked to one other rail node
except for the the last node, which has no links to rails.
 
A rail is usually co-incident with a piece of geometry, like an actual metal rail
or the edge of a halfpipe, or pool.
 
There are two possible types of rail, normal and a looped.
 
A normal rail is just a list of nodes, each one linked ot the next
 
A looped rail is a single loop of nodes.  Each node only links to one other node
 
The format of a rail node would be:
 
 dw RAILDEF or RAILPOINT
 ... links, angles, etc
 dw Flags

the format of flags is 
	Bit 15
	Bit 14
	Bit 13
	Bit 12
	Bit 11
	Bit 10
	Bit 9
	Bit 8
	Bit 7
	Bit 6
	Bit 4+5  - Number of players 
	Bits 3-0 - Terrain Type
 
 
 
*/



#include "globals.h"
#include "bit.h"
#include "bit2.h"
#include "rail.h"
#include "mech.h"
#include "m3dutils.h"
#include "trig.h"
#include "symbols.h"
